post_text:
Good evening everyone,

The North East High School Yearbooks are in! Seniors, your book should be mailed to your house. Please do not come to school. If you bought a High School yearbook, please pick up your book on either Thursday, June 25 from noon to 4:00 p.m. or Friday, June 26 from 8:00 a.m. to noon. Please drive by the gym lobby doors and a yearbook staff member will deliver the book to you in your vehicle. Please be sure to wear a mask and we will be practicing safe social distancing procedures during this time. As of now, we do not have extra books for sale. If we do in the future, we will let you know.

Have a great night!

Mrs. Fitch and Mr. Denevic

post_text: North East School District is currently taking Kindergarten registration paperwork for the 2020-21 academic year. You can obtain a registration packet by calling the Earle C. Davis office at 725-8671 x3050 or emailing gschwartz@nesd1.org. Kindergarten registration is currently scheduled for July 8 from 8:30 a.m. - 4:00 p.m. Parents who have already contacted the office will be receiving a letter with their designated time to attend. In order to be eligible to register, the child must be 5 years of age by May 31, 2020. If you have a packet to turn in, you can drop it off during the lunch pick-up at the High School 10:30 a.m. - 11:30 a.m. Monday - Thursday.

A message from Mr. Emick regarding the NEIE fundraiser:
Please be advised that we do plan to distribute all ordered items from our spring fundraiser as soon as we are able to do so. We are currently following the Erie County directive for stay put expectations. As soon as we receive further guidance, we will communicate with parents accordingly. Please let your family and friends know that we fully intend to get everything out to those who ordered from our fundraiser. We will continue to share out information as we move forward. Thank you and be well!

post_text:
Good Afternoon NE Family:

Due to parents now working from home, we are reassessing technology access for our students. We are asking all families to complete the technology survey. The survey is posted on the district website or it can be accessed at survey.nesd1.org. Please read the survey directions carefully. COMPLETE ONLY ONE SURVEY PER HOUSEHOLD by noon on Saturday, March 21st. Please share and help other families complete the survey that may not have access to technology.

There are also several updates and resources on our website; specifically contained in the FAQ’s document.

Information is changing hourly; please be patient and enjoy this time with your families. The Board, administration, and staff are working tirelessly to ensure we have a sound education plan in place for our children.

Sincerely,

Dr. Michele S. Hartzell, Superintendent

and

the Board, Administration, Faculty, & Staff of the NESD

post_text:
Twelve (12) NE Intermediate students visited the Tom Ridge Environmental Center for a Problem-Solving Hack-a-Thon presented by the Regional Science Consortium. The students were presented a challenge/problem and had to develop ways they think would fix the problem. Today's challenge was to create a new, energy-efficient school. Before working in their groups, students learned what sustainability means, were presented information on products and ideas that are currently being used that are environmentally friendly, and learned all about the Tom Ridge Environmental Center and what products were used in building it. The students then worked in groups to create a prototype of a new school using some of these ideas and presented this information to a panel of judges and students from five different districts.
Our students did a wonderful job earning a silver, gold, and platinum for their presentations and prototypes!

post_text:
Last week's Career Cafe at NEIE welcomed Mr. Kevin Fisher.
Mr. Fisher works for Wabtec and came to discuss careers in Engineering. He spoke to some of our 5th grade students about the STEM field, the various types of engineering careers and the daily tasks/duties in his position. Mr. Fisher also talked to the students about what subjects in school to take and the skills needed in order to be an engineer. It was a very informative session and the students got a lot of information from the presentation.

post_text: Ms. Caryn Krahe, Art Teacher at NEMS, took a group of students to the Erie Art Museum for a tour. They had a guided tour with interactive and hands-on activities. They even got to hold an original Picasso print! The students that went were ones who completed the Inktober art challenge. Inktober is a drawing challenge in the month of October that gives 31 prompts for sketches to be completed throughout the entire month. The students who went on the trip completed all 31 sketches in October. Looks like they had a great time!

post_text:
The boys cross country team will be representing North East High School once again at the PIAA State Championships this Saturday, November 2nd. The “Long Gold Line” placed second to Grove City at the District 10 meet this past weekend and punched their tickets to Hershey. The team, led by seniors Zane Courtwright, Tony Haskins, Tanner Kloss and Jason Seevers, will step to the starting line at 12:30 pm on Saturday. The Pickers are also supported by a talented underclassmen group that includes junior Brock Pennington, sophomore Ben Leonard and freshman Lucas Boyd.
The state meet will be the last for long time head coach Dick Gregg as he is set to retire from coaching cross country at the conclusion of the season. Coach Gregg is recognized throughout District 10 and the state for heading one of the states premier programs. We wish Coach Gregg and the Pickers good luck at Hershey!
Streaming and on demand coverage information can be found at https://pcntv.com/crosscountry/.
